1
00:00:31,476 --> 00:00:32,684
Again.

2
00:00:33,017 --> 00:00:34,450
Every time.

3
00:00:34,950 --> 00:00:37,563
It--it's really amazing,
you know?

4
00:00:37,663 --> 00:00:40,955
No matter how little milk
you put on your cereal,

5
00:00:41,055 --> 00:00:43,383
there's always
too much left at the end.

6
00:00:43,659 --> 00:00:46,834
I mean, you would think it would
be possible to judge it right.

7
00:00:46,934 --> 00:00:49,291
You know, maybe put in
just the right amount of milk

8
00:00:49,391 --> 00:00:50,928
so it all comes out even?

9
00:00:51,028 --> 00:00:53,631
But no.
Th--there's always too much.

10
00:00:54,508 --> 00:00:55,811
It's just...

11
00:00:57,476 --> 00:00:58,991
Shit!
So, what?

12
00:00:59,091 --> 00:01:02,634
You end up havin to pour in more cereal
that you probably don't even want,

13
00:01:02,734 --> 00:01:04,960
Or--or having to pick up the bowl
and slurp it!

14
00:01:05,060 --> 00:01:07,395
Like you're
some kind of a dog!

15
00:01:07,495 --> 00:01:10,244
There's no reprieve!
It's every time!

16
00:01:10,344 --> 00:01:13,252
It just digs, and digs,
and digs,

17
00:01:13,352 --> 00:01:16,037
until you just can't
take it anymore...!

18
00:01:16,138 --> 00:01:18,379
I wish I were dead!

19
00:01:43,712 --> 00:01:44,768
Ugh!

20
00:01:44,868 --> 00:01:48,051
I don't believe it!
I'm gonna die!

21
00:02:06,141 --> 00:02:07,817
I don't need this,
you know.

22
00:02:08,463 --> 00:02:11,577
Flies are the filthiest creatures
on the planet.

23
00:02:11,677 --> 00:02:15,098
The number one
carriers of disease.

24
00:02:17,481 --> 00:02:22,025
And they're pathetically stupid.
The stupidest of all bugs.

25
00:02:22,125 --> 00:02:23,774
I mean...
You've seen 'em, right?

26
00:02:23,874 --> 00:02:26,326
They--they sit around
cleaning their hands all the time,

27
00:02:26,426 --> 00:02:28,182
you know, like it matters?

28
00:02:28,282 --> 00:02:29,677
So, I go in my backyard.

29
00:02:29,777 --> 00:02:32,317
There's a piece of dog crap
on the ground.

30
00:02:32,417 --> 00:02:37,426
A piece of dog crap.
Fly sitting on it, cleaning his hands.

31
00:02:37,526 --> 00:02:40,524
How incredibly stupid
would you have to be?

32
00:02:43,879 --> 00:02:47,396
"What is this shit on here?"

33
00:02:49,982 --> 00:02:53,746
"It's there again.
What is this shit?"

34
00:02:54,500 --> 00:02:56,909
They're dirty,
disgusting creatures

35
00:02:57,009 --> 00:02:59,262
that should be
gathered up and exterminated.

36
00:02:59,362 --> 00:03:01,787
And I'm not that interested
in that whole food chain thing.

37
00:03:01,887 --> 00:03:04,103
"Pollinisation" or
whatever the hell it is.

38
00:03:04,203 --> 00:03:06,945
I'd gladly give up
an occasional honeydew

39
00:03:07,045 --> 00:03:12,253
if it meant being forever rid
of those useless, pathetic, vile, horrible,

40
00:03:12,353 --> 00:03:15,811
disease riddled, wretched little
flying devil bugs!

41
00:03:19,086 --> 00:03:21,136
Oh, great.

42
00:03:23,077 --> 00:03:24,820
I don't even know
why I read this, you know.

43
00:03:24,920 --> 00:03:27,256
 Everything in it
just makes you sick.

44
00:03:27,764 --> 00:03:31,802
Yesterday, I read about
this guy that killed his sister-in-law,

45
00:03:31,902 --> 00:03:33,606
and then his brother.

46
00:03:33,706 --> 00:03:36,716
Right, so he goe's to trial.
He is found innocent

47
00:03:36,816 --> 00:03:41,505
by reason of insanity,
and gets out in four years.

48
00:03:42,240 --> 00:03:44,545
Four years!

49
00:03:48,086 --> 00:03:49,782
You know what
I think they should do?

50
00:03:49,882 --> 00:03:52,800
Let's say somebody kills
Amy Lou Rogers.

51
00:03:53,224 --> 00:03:55,047
I think they should
lock him in his cell;

52
00:03:55,147 --> 00:03:56,808
and when they
bury Amy Lou,

53
00:03:56,908 --> 00:03:59,972
they should put the key
to the cell in her hand.

54
00:04:00,072 --> 00:04:02,394
That way,
when a few years goes by,

55
00:04:02,494 --> 00:04:07,265
and the guy starts whining:
"Hey, when are you gonna let me out?"

56
00:04:07,365 --> 00:04:09,724
"I've been in here
a really long time."

57
00:04:09,824 --> 00:04:11,807
"When do I get out?"

58
00:04:11,907 --> 00:04:14,146
You just go:
"Hey, don't sweat it, pal."

59
00:04:14,246 --> 00:04:17,074
"As soon as Amy Lou
comes back to life,

60
00:04:17,174 --> 00:04:20,409
digs her way out, and
waltzes in here with the key,

61
00:04:20,509 --> 00:04:21,601
you're walking!"

62
00:04:21,701 --> 00:04:24,377
"24 hours tops,
you're on the streets!"

63
00:04:27,182 --> 00:04:29,251
But you know
what really gets me mad?

64
00:04:30,445 --> 00:04:34,118
I bought these natural
watermelon popsicles.

65
00:04:34,694 --> 00:04:39,627
On the box, It said: "100% natural,
100% watermelon."

66
00:04:39,727 --> 00:04:42,240
So I thought:
"Hey, I love watermelon."

67
00:04:42,340 --> 00:04:43,940
"I love popsicles."

68
00:04:44,040 --> 00:04:46,830
"This should be
the perfect thing for me."

69
00:04:47,905 --> 00:04:49,799
So I take a bite.

70
00:04:49,899 --> 00:04:52,266
And I notice there's something
in my mouth.

71
00:04:52,366 --> 00:04:54,665
Something small and hard.

72
00:04:54,765 --> 00:04:58,528
So I spit it out...
It was a seed.

73
00:04:59,410 --> 00:05:00,925
A seed!

74
00:05:01,025 --> 00:05:06,920
They actually put
watermelon seeds in the popsicles!

75
00:05:07,656 --> 00:05:10,700
What is the possible
marketing strategy here?

76
00:05:10,800 --> 00:05:12,883
"Yes!
Watermelon popsicles!"

77
00:05:12,983 --> 00:05:15,658
"With all the annoyance
of real watermelon!"

78
00:05:15,758 --> 00:05:17,301
I mean, what's next?

79
00:05:17,401 --> 00:05:19,937
Banana flavored popsicles
with skin?

80
00:05:20,037 --> 00:05:22,809
Coconut popsicles with a
thick, though husk?

81
00:05:22,909 --> 00:05:25,695
It makes me sick!
How do they expect me to eat this!

82
00:05:25,795 --> 00:05:29,058
What do they take me for?
It is totally unacceptable!

83
00:05:29,158 --> 00:05:31,486
And don't expect me
to go along with it, like:

84
00:05:31,586 --> 00:05:36,502
"Oh, no problem!
Seeds in the popsicles? That's great!"

85
00:05:36,602 --> 00:05:40,402
"I love that..."
Uuuugh!

86
00:05:45,556 --> 00:05:48,726
I don't know...
I didn't ask for this, you know.

87
00:05:49,787 --> 00:05:52,318
I didn't... I didn't ask
to be born.

88
00:05:54,669 --> 00:05:58,318
Sometimes I just wanna...
I just wanna shut everything out.

89
00:05:59,547 --> 00:06:01,258
Just relax.

90
00:06:14,163 --> 00:06:15,357
What the...?

91
00:06:16,978 --> 00:06:19,915
I can...
I can relax later or something.

92
00:06:20,510 --> 00:06:23,607
Yeah.
I'm no--I'm not tired.

93
00:06:23,707 --> 00:06:25,002
I should be working.

94
00:06:25,724 --> 00:06:29,051
Yeah.
Get some work done.

95
00:06:29,591 --> 00:06:31,772
I u--I used to
like my job, you know.

96
00:06:31,872 --> 00:06:34,066
I write children's books.

97
00:06:34,166 --> 00:06:36,903
Everything was going great.
You know, I work my own hours.

98
00:06:37,003 --> 00:06:38,947
Something I like.
Good pay.

99
00:06:39,047 --> 00:06:41,068
Boss was really tolerable.

100
00:06:41,168 --> 00:06:42,887
- Thane, how are you?
- I'm good.

101
00:06:42,987 --> 00:06:44,914
I just read
your latest submission.

102
00:06:45,014 --> 00:06:48,378
Now, it's a little rough, and we
might have to tone it down a bit.

103
00:06:48,478 --> 00:06:50,417
But I like the way
you think, Thane.

104
00:06:50,855 --> 00:06:53,810
You are very creative.
Very different.

105
00:06:53,910 --> 00:06:55,156
I like that.

106
00:06:55,567 --> 00:06:57,954
Thanks, Marvin.
I'll rework it.

107
00:06:58,054 --> 00:07:01,517
You know... you should
cheer up a little bit, Thane.

108
00:07:02,039 --> 00:07:04,291
You're a bright kid.
You got a lot going for you.

109
00:07:04,392 --> 00:07:05,975
Try smiling a little.

110
00:07:06,808 --> 00:07:08,964
Smiling's never really been
one of my strong points.

111
00:07:09,064 --> 00:07:11,683
Well, give it a try.
It's good for business.

112
00:07:11,783 --> 00:07:15,329
You'd be surprised how many business deals
are made on personality alone.

113
00:07:15,428 --> 00:07:16,938
<i>Then he gets married.</i>

114
00:07:17,298 --> 00:07:18,766
He marries this...

115
00:07:20,209 --> 00:07:21,204
...woman...

116
00:07:21,304 --> 00:07:23,440
...who is, like, half his age,
which I have no problem with,

117
00:07:23,540 --> 00:07:26,044
but she's, like,
this horrible person.

118
00:07:26,143 --> 00:07:29,062
She's inhuman.
Melanie.

119
00:07:31,307 --> 00:07:33,253
Me-la-nie.

120
00:07:33,353 --> 00:07:35,554
- Marvin!
- Princess!

121
00:07:36,308 --> 00:07:38,889
You have to get going, darling.
You have a very big lunch meeting.

122
00:07:38,990 --> 00:07:42,901
Oh, uh... Thane, I'd like you
to meet my wife.

123
00:07:43,321 --> 00:07:45,079
- This is Melanie.
- Oh, darling.

124
00:07:45,179 --> 00:07:48,394
Please, let's not get into this.
We barely have enough time as it is.

125
00:07:48,494 --> 00:07:50,391
- Well, I guess you're right.
- Of course I am.

126
00:07:50,491 --> 00:07:51,910
Now let's just
get you to lunch,

127
00:07:52,011 --> 00:07:54,501
and you let me handle
everything here at the office.

128
00:07:55,677 --> 00:07:58,153
- I don't like him.
<i>- Now she makes all the decisions,</i>

129
00:07:58,253 --> 00:08:01,366
which wouldn't be so bad
if someone else relayed them,

130
00:08:01,466 --> 00:08:03,685
but you have to
listen to her speak.

131
00:08:03,785 --> 00:08:05,191
She's totally self-indulgent.

132
00:08:05,291 --> 00:08:07,604
She could listen to
her own voice for hours.

133
00:08:07,704 --> 00:08:11,734
Not only do I not have a clue
as to what my boss sees in her,

134
00:08:11,834 --> 00:08:15,560
but I would love to know how the earth
could just keep from opening up

135
00:08:15,660 --> 00:08:20,904
<i>and sucking her into some deep,
dark, multidimensional void!</i>

136
00:08:21,004 --> 00:08:22,977
<i>"You have to
make your dead line,</i>

137
00:08:23,077 --> 00:08:26,535
<i>or we won't be able
to get the copy in on time."</i>

138
00:08:26,635 --> 00:08:29,138
<i>She's always giving orders
that don't matter.</i>

139
00:08:29,238 --> 00:08:33,004
Or she'll go off one some huge,
pathetic, condescending,

140
00:08:33,104 --> 00:08:36,435
inaccurate lecture
on the meaning of life.

141
00:08:36,535 --> 00:08:39,628
<i>"Some people are just
less capable than others."</i>

142
00:08:39,728 --> 00:08:43,125
"People depending on
their upbringing and nationality,

143
00:08:43,226 --> 00:08:48,013
<i>have different ability levels, and
have to be put into their correct category."</i>

144
00:08:48,969 --> 00:08:53,408
Nightmare! It's like this incredibly
articulate way of saying:

145
00:08:53,508 --> 00:08:56,216
"I'm hopelessly prejudiced.
Sorry."

146
00:08:56,316 --> 00:08:58,952
But the horror
of all of this,

147
00:08:59,052 --> 00:09:03,409
is you can't say anything,
because it's the boss' wife.

148
00:09:03,509 --> 00:09:07,483
Right? So--so you just sit there and nod
so you don't lose your job,

149
00:09:07,583 --> 00:09:09,338
and you hear yourself
saying things, like:

150
00:09:09,438 --> 00:09:11,955
"Yeah... I guess."

151
00:09:12,055 --> 00:09:15,378
Then you feel like the most
spineless loser on the planet,

152
00:09:15,478 --> 00:09:17,699
because you've sacrificed
your self-worth,

153
00:09:17,799 --> 00:09:20,242
and everything you value
and believe in,

154
00:09:20,342 --> 00:09:24,411
because it might hurt you financially
if you speak up.

155
00:09:25,314 --> 00:09:28,677
I-i-it's amazing what some people
are capable of.

156
00:09:36,126 --> 00:09:39,304
Great.
It's not even 10 o'clock yet.

157
00:09:42,312 --> 00:09:46,172
Hey, dorkhead!
Turn it down!

158
00:09:47,791 --> 00:09:50,315
This guy's a perpetual
thorn in my side.

159
00:09:50,415 --> 00:09:52,505
He plays music,
if that's what it is,

160
00:09:52,605 --> 00:09:56,232
all day, at a volume that any
amphitheater would be envious of.

161
00:09:56,332 --> 00:09:58,241
He never hears me yell,
which is no surprise.

162
00:09:58,341 --> 00:10:01,556
I'm sure there's blood
constantly spewing from his ears.

163
00:10:03,354 --> 00:10:06,048
There he goes.
There he goes.

164
00:10:06,148 --> 00:10:10,215
Now, you tell me...
you tell me, just...

165
00:10:10,315 --> 00:10:11,737
What the hell is that?

166
00:10:11,837 --> 00:10:15,270
I mean... I mean, what is he doing,
some sort of gigantic boot dance?

167
00:10:15,370 --> 00:10:16,626
I mean, what is that?

168
00:10:18,139 --> 00:10:22,687
I can't even remotely imagine
just what in the hell...!

169
00:10:25,434 --> 00:10:28,223
Oh my gosh.
I hope he didn't trip.

170
00:10:28,323 --> 00:10:30,668
And hit his temple on
the power button of the stereo.

171
00:10:30,768 --> 00:10:33,722
Accidentally turning it off, and
knocking himself into a permanent coma.

172
00:10:33,822 --> 00:10:35,676
That would be terrible.
What would I do?

173
00:10:36,964 --> 00:10:40,361
I guess I should wait a couple of weeks
and see if something starts to smell.

174
00:10:45,589 --> 00:10:49,341
- Yeah.
- <i>Tonight. At 8 o'clock.</i>

175
00:10:50,508 --> 00:10:51,772
What?

176
00:10:53,307 --> 00:10:54,566
What does that mean?

177
00:10:55,640 --> 00:10:58,526
What the hell is that?
8 o'clock?

178
00:10:59,416 --> 00:11:02,325
It's just some--some
jerk or something...

179
00:11:03,557 --> 00:11:06,158
You know it used to be
peaceful around here.

180
00:11:06,693 --> 00:11:10,084
The dog.
I forgot to bring in the dog.

181
00:11:19,430 --> 00:11:22,591
Sorry about that.
This is my dog, Pete.

182
00:11:22,691 --> 00:11:25,623
Please, don't think I'm crazy.
I'm not.

183
00:11:25,723 --> 00:11:28,242
It's just that I don't believe
in real pets.

184
00:11:28,342 --> 00:11:32,522
Sure, I know people love them.
They're cute, they're cuddly.

185
00:11:32,622 --> 00:11:37,033
It's just that I have a hard time
imagining giving a place in my life

186
00:11:37,133 --> 00:11:40,443
to some beast, that if worse
came to worse, would turn on me.

187
00:11:40,543 --> 00:11:43,874
Because, that's the reality of it,
whether you want to admit it or not.

188
00:11:43,974 --> 00:11:44,916
They're animals.

189
00:11:45,016 --> 00:11:46,781
And if there was suddenly
a food shortage,

190
00:11:46,881 --> 00:11:50,116
and the opportunity arose,
your precious little Fifi

191
00:11:50,216 --> 00:11:54,017
wouldn't think twice about putting you
on the old smorgasbord list.

192
00:11:54,336 --> 00:11:57,219
People just believe
what they wanna believe.

193
00:12:07,113 --> 00:12:10,127
Remember when that plane
crashed in the snow,

194
00:12:10,227 --> 00:12:12,285
and some of the people survived?

195
00:12:12,553 --> 00:12:14,563
But they didn't get rescued
for a really long time

196
00:12:14,664 --> 00:12:18,762
and they actually had to eat
the other passengers to stay alive?

197
00:12:19,997 --> 00:12:23,839
I mean, that is a big,
moral decision.

198
00:12:24,493 --> 00:12:27,903
If your life depended on it,
do you think you could do it?

199
00:12:28,627 --> 00:12:30,855
I don't know,
I've thought about it a lot.

200
00:12:31,814 --> 00:12:33,894
I figure they didn't
do anything wrong.

201
00:12:33,994 --> 00:12:35,785
You know, I mean,
it was life and death.

202
00:12:35,885 --> 00:12:38,425
I think I probably could
if my life was at stake.

203
00:12:38,525 --> 00:12:42,653
I mean, it would have to be
a major, major deal, right?

204
00:12:42,753 --> 00:12:45,239
Not like a long layover
or something like that.

205
00:12:45,339 --> 00:12:48,647
I mean, none of it's, like:
"It's late in Dallas, the snack shop's closed;

206
00:12:48,747 --> 00:12:50,174
let's eat Larry!"
You know.

207
00:12:50,274 --> 00:12:51,884
I'd never go along with that.

208
00:12:51,984 --> 00:12:55,538
I don't, uh...
think it's morally correct.

209
00:12:56,386 --> 00:12:59,037
But, if it was life and death,
line 'em up.

210
00:12:59,137 --> 00:13:01,060
Snack time, that's what I say.
Because, you gotta remember:

211
00:13:01,160 --> 00:13:04,475
These people died in a plane crash.
You're not murdering anyone.

212
00:13:04,575 --> 00:13:05,468
I could eat them.

213
00:13:05,568 --> 00:13:07,917
Or maybe if a guy was
walking along, and he tripped,

214
00:13:08,017 --> 00:13:10,264
and he hit his head on a rock,
and he wasn't dead,

215
00:13:10,365 --> 00:13:12,861
but you knew he was gonna die...

216
00:13:13,489 --> 00:13:14,518
I could probably
start eating him.

217
00:13:14,618 --> 00:13:17,726
You know...
Like a coma.

218
00:13:17,826 --> 00:13:20,629
But if he woke up, I'd stop.
'Cause I'd figure: "Hey,

219
00:13:20,729 --> 00:13:25,215
that's normal, human etiquette, and
I'm not crossing that line for anybody."

220
00:13:25,315 --> 00:13:26,593
"I'm sorry."

221
00:13:30,823 --> 00:13:32,244
What the hell was--

222
00:13:32,616 --> 00:13:33,867
Now, what the--

223
00:13:35,836 --> 00:13:36,921
I must need sleep.

224
00:13:40,096 --> 00:13:41,346
What?

225
00:13:44,224 --> 00:13:45,474
What!

226
00:13:47,936 --> 00:13:50,458
- Hi, sir, how are you today?
- Don't ask.

227
00:13:50,848 --> 00:13:53,778
- You seem like an intelligent man.
- What are you selling?

228
00:13:54,608 --> 00:13:56,214
Well, it's not so much
what I'm selling, sir,

229
00:13:56,314 --> 00:13:58,030
as it is what I have to offer.

230
00:13:58,129 --> 00:14:01,511
Oh, what do you have to offer
that just happens to cost money?

231
00:14:02,145 --> 00:14:03,535
I offer security.

232
00:14:03,636 --> 00:14:05,941
- Insurrance?
- That's right, sir.

233
00:14:07,148 --> 00:14:10,413
I am so sorry.
Please, come in.

234
00:14:10,513 --> 00:14:12,446
I... I feel like an idiot.

235
00:14:15,013 --> 00:14:19,861
- I hope this is okay for you.
