468
00:26:52,189 --> 00:26:54,859
Uh, no, I was...
Laying down here next to it.

469
00:26:55,014 --> 00:26:56,428
<i>Laying down?</i>

470
00:26:56,529 --> 00:26:59,424
<i>It's nearly 1 in the afternoon,
you can't lay down now.</i>

471
00:26:59,911 --> 00:27:02,333
<i>It's only a few hours
until 8!</i>

472
00:27:04,151 --> 00:27:05,405
Mom?

473
00:27:12,224 --> 00:27:14,188
- Hello?
<i>- Why'd you hang up?</i>

474
00:27:14,288 --> 00:27:16,844
I didn't hang up.
I got cut off.

475
00:27:16,944 --> 00:27:18,681
<i>What was that you said
about 8 o'clock?</i>

476
00:27:18,781 --> 00:27:21,569
- What?
- You said something about 8 o'clock.

477
00:27:21,669 --> 00:27:23,750
<i>No I didn't.
Are you okay?</i>

478
00:27:23,850 --> 00:27:26,318
Look, Mo--Mom, I... I gott--I gotta go.
Okay? There's someone at the door.

479
00:27:26,418 --> 00:27:28,752
I-I'll talk to you later.
Okay, see you, bye.

480
00:27:34,150 --> 00:27:35,561
This is crazy.

481
00:27:36,341 --> 00:27:37,836
I gotta get some work done.

482
00:27:43,270 --> 00:27:46,007
Why do I have to
please other people with my work?

483
00:27:47,037 --> 00:27:51,314
I mean, I work countless hours
on valuable product,

484
00:27:51,414 --> 00:27:53,514
just to see it
get turned down.

485
00:27:53,614 --> 00:27:56,306
And who loses here?
Is it me?

486
00:27:56,406 --> 00:27:59,651
No. No, it's not me.
It's the kids.

487
00:27:59,751 --> 00:28:01,474
The kids lose.

488
00:28:01,574 --> 00:28:05,505
Valuable information
and mental growth cut off

489
00:28:05,605 --> 00:28:09,170
because someone didn't have
the foresight to see the need.

490
00:28:09,270 --> 00:28:11,161
Here... I-I'll show you.

491
00:28:12,750 --> 00:28:14,353
H-here's one
they turned down.

492
00:28:14,453 --> 00:28:18,145
Now here's a book that
does more than just kill time.

493
00:28:18,245 --> 00:28:22,529
It helps the kid to spot the symptoms
if his mother's being unfaithful.

494
00:28:22,888 --> 00:28:24,282
Here's another one.

495
00:28:27,072 --> 00:28:30,731
Now, they really
misinterpreted this one.

496
00:28:30,831 --> 00:28:34,548
My whole intent here, was to
have an instruction manual

497
00:28:34,648 --> 00:28:37,340
that even a child
could understand.

498
00:28:37,440 --> 00:28:42,334
Only to be used
in grave circumstances.

499
00:28:42,434 --> 00:28:44,962
I mean, you know, like,
somebody's choking on a chicken bone,

500
00:28:45,062 --> 00:28:47,771
and they have to be taken to the hospital,
but there are no adults around,

501
00:28:47,872 --> 00:28:50,268
I mean, what are you gonna do,
let them die?

502
00:28:50,872 --> 00:28:54,252
Yeah, you know, I guess
some people probably would.

503
00:28:58,544 --> 00:29:02,270
Now this...
is my pride and joy.

504
00:29:02,720 --> 00:29:04,763
I haven't even
told them about it yet.

505
00:29:04,863 --> 00:29:07,478
It's a pop-up book.
My first one.

506
00:29:07,956 --> 00:29:10,219
It's called
<i>What Happened to Grandma?</i>

507
00:29:10,319 --> 00:29:13,139
Well, that's one of the
working titles.

508
00:29:13,239 --> 00:29:16,596
It deals with the passing
of a loved one.

509
00:29:16,864 --> 00:29:19,884
But the beautiful thing is,
as you can see,

510
00:29:19,985 --> 00:29:21,584
when you open it up...

511
00:29:24,790 --> 00:29:28,772
As this can be a very trying
and traumatic time for children,

512
00:29:28,872 --> 00:29:31,892
this book helps point out
that Grandma isn't gone forever,

513
00:29:31,992 --> 00:29:35,283
she's just sort of
relocated without her body.

514
00:29:35,383 --> 00:29:37,979
It also points out
the very real possibility

515
00:29:38,080 --> 00:29:42,037
that they're just one little car wreck away
from going there themselves.

516
00:29:43,330 --> 00:29:47,244
But... there's no hope.
They'll probably reject this one, too.

517
00:29:47,344 --> 00:29:51,661
And you know why? Because they're
trying to keep children mindless.

518
00:29:51,761 --> 00:29:56,911
They're trying to block them from having
the ability to think for themselves.

519
00:29:57,787 --> 00:30:03,084
To think that the futures of hundreds
of thousands of innocent children

520
00:30:03,184 --> 00:30:07,975
are being programmed to do and think
whatever Big Brother tells them,

521
00:30:08,075 --> 00:30:09,951
just makes me sick!

522
00:30:10,051 --> 00:30:14,082
I have no intention
of participating any longer

523
00:30:14,182 --> 00:30:16,913
in the vegetation
of the young mind!

524
00:30:17,013 --> 00:30:20,995
I won't do it!
I'd rather be dead!

525
00:30:23,548 --> 00:30:25,277
Oh, great.

526
00:32:09,024 --> 00:32:10,774
You're mine.

527
00:32:21,879 --> 00:32:24,650
The door was open,
so I let myself in.

528
00:32:27,231 --> 00:32:28,869
Were you
trying to get this?

529
00:32:28,969 --> 00:32:29,922
No.

530
00:32:30,499 --> 00:32:32,321
I wa--I was just messin' around.

531
00:32:32,421 --> 00:32:36,503
"Messin' around?"
"Messin' around," he says?

532
00:32:36,603 --> 00:32:40,263
He's got three deadlines hanging
over his head, and he's messin' around?

533
00:32:42,338 --> 00:32:44,837
You had better
pull yourself together, mister!

534
00:32:44,937 --> 00:32:46,907
You are threading
on thin ice!

535
00:32:47,007 --> 00:32:48,778
I have not been impressed
with your work of late,

536
00:32:48,878 --> 00:32:50,683
and if I don't see some sort
of improvement soon,

537
00:32:50,783 --> 00:32:53,296
there's going to be
all kinds of trouble!

538
00:32:54,371 --> 00:32:57,205
These kinds of jobs don't
grow on trees, you know, Thane.

539
00:32:57,305 --> 00:33:01,863
There are a lot of talented people out there
that would kill to be in your shoes.

540
00:33:01,963 --> 00:33:06,183
You've had it pretty easy in the past,
and I tell you it has hurt you.

541
00:33:10,021 --> 00:33:12,287
The problem with you is,
you are not a dedicated worker.

542
00:33:12,387 --> 00:33:13,645
I need an ashtray.

543
00:33:14,307 --> 00:33:16,394
Oh...
I don--I don't have one.

544
00:33:17,005 --> 00:33:18,466
Fine, I'll use this.

545
00:33:20,828 --> 00:33:23,381
It is very important that you
become a dedicated worker, Thane.

546
00:33:23,481 --> 00:33:25,752
Your future at Shangri-La Books
depends on it.

547
00:33:25,852 --> 00:33:28,938
You've gotta think about this, Thane.
Your future is at stake!

548
00:33:29,038 --> 00:33:32,623
I'll tell you, Marvin is
not going to like this.

549
00:33:32,723 --> 00:33:34,721
No, Marvin wouldn't care
about any of this.

550
00:33:34,821 --> 00:33:38,107
And Marvin wouldn't have
broken into my house!

551
00:33:39,567 --> 00:33:41,870
Unless--unless the door were open.

552
00:33:42,467 --> 00:33:44,562
Then he... he might
have let himself in.

553
00:33:44,662 --> 00:33:47,166
I mean...
Who wouldn't, right?

554
00:33:48,297 --> 00:33:51,037
I cant' stand it!
I... I can't stand it!

555
00:33:51,137 --> 00:33:53,812
I'm a weasel!
Just tell her off!

556
00:33:53,912 --> 00:33:55,879
Wy can't I just
tell her off?

557
00:33:55,979 --> 00:33:58,901
I'll lose my job.
I don't wanna lose my job.

558
00:33:59,001 --> 00:34:00,412
This is a nightmare!

559
00:34:00,513 --> 00:34:03,450
See, now, I'm just gonna sit there,
and never bring up the fact

560
00:34:03,549 --> 00:34:06,916
that she's a horrible person,
no matter what she says.

561
00:34:07,016 --> 00:34:10,423
I don't believe this!
I wish I were dead!

562
00:34:10,523 --> 00:34:16,425
So, let me tell you, I am so tired
of all the inept people at the office.

563
00:34:16,525 --> 00:34:19,161
A'll I'm surrounded by
is ineptness.

564
00:34:19,261 --> 00:34:22,642
Now don't get me wrong, Thane,
you are not totally inept.

565
00:34:23,041 --> 00:34:25,233
Of course you need a lot of work,
but who doesn't?

566
00:34:25,333 --> 00:34:28,707
It's all upbringing.
I'm one of the lucky ones.

567
00:34:28,807 --> 00:34:30,408
Take minorities, for instance.

568
00:34:30,508 --> 00:34:33,919
They're not inferior because
they are genetically different.

569
00:34:34,019 --> 00:34:36,869
They're inferior
because of upbringing.

570
00:34:37,426 --> 00:34:41,020
How--how do you listen to
a statement like that, and just sit there?

571
00:34:41,120 --> 00:34:43,279
Oh, man!
I'm a wreck.

572
00:34:43,888 --> 00:34:46,270
I... I can't deal with it.

573
00:34:47,542 --> 00:34:49,190
What--what am I saying?

574
00:34:50,052 --> 00:34:51,558
What am I saying?

575
00:34:52,094 --> 00:34:57,094
How important is a job
if you have to sacrifice your integrity?

576
00:34:58,150 --> 00:34:59,622
I won't have it.

577
00:35:00,718 --> 00:35:02,853
I won't have it!

578
00:35:03,502 --> 00:35:07,157
Wait a second!
Now just wait a second!

579
00:35:07,257 --> 00:35:08,814
You're wrong.

580
00:35:09,422 --> 00:35:12,223
You're racist,
and you're wrong.

581
00:35:12,323 --> 00:35:14,641
And I--and I'm sorry,
if you wanna get me fired,

582
00:35:14,741 --> 00:35:17,548
because I don't agree with
your perjudicial statements,

583
00:35:17,648 --> 00:35:21,086
fine, but what you said
was wrong.

584
00:35:22,632 --> 00:35:25,576
That sounded pretty good.
I'll try that.

585
00:35:25,676 --> 00:35:30,038
For instance, I was watching
one of these freedom rallies on the news.

586
00:35:30,138 --> 00:35:32,467
Some other backwards country,
I'm not sure which one.

587
00:35:32,567 --> 00:35:34,107
And I started thinking:

588
00:35:34,794 --> 00:35:38,173
"How horrible freedom can be."

589
00:35:38,646 --> 00:35:40,981
"Our country could
learn something from this."

590
00:35:41,081 --> 00:35:43,564
The only people
making the decisions,

591
00:35:43,664 --> 00:35:45,731
should be those few
that are mentally capable.

592
00:35:45,831 --> 00:35:48,849
You can't give the general public
a say in what goes on.

593
00:35:48,949 --> 00:35:52,080
They're unable to render
an intelligent decision.

594
00:35:53,850 --> 00:35:55,586
There are very few smart enough
and wise enough

595
00:35:55,686 --> 00:35:57,278
to be making those decisions.

596
00:35:57,378 --> 00:36:00,615
And you can usually
a person's worth by their income.

597
00:36:00,715 --> 00:36:04,152
I think you should only be allowed
to vote if you make over, say...

598
00:36:04,874 --> 00:36:06,216
200,000 a year.

599
00:36:06,457 --> 00:36:08,874
It's just plain, common sense,
don't you agree, Thane?

600
00:36:10,367 --> 00:36:13,586
Thane?
Don't you agree?

601
00:36:14,392 --> 00:36:15,645
Well...

602
00:36:18,609 --> 00:36:19,903
Yeah...

603
00:36:23,163 --> 00:36:26,869
I don't believe it!
How can I agree with her?

604
00:36:27,082 --> 00:36:29,076
There's no excuse!
I should be killed!

605
00:36:29,176 --> 00:36:33,189
I should be skinned alive
and then rolled around in salt!

606
00:36:33,776 --> 00:36:36,290
Now...
About your work.

607
00:36:36,390 --> 00:36:38,420
As of late, I've been
very unimpressed.

608
00:36:38,520 --> 00:36:41,716
You seem bent on these
unconventional tactics

609
00:36:41,816 --> 00:36:44,302
that frankly, I think stink.

610
00:36:45,041 --> 00:36:47,965
I came to pick up your new book
you've been so secretive about.

611
00:36:48,065 --> 00:36:49,453
Is it finished?

612
00:36:50,079 --> 00:36:52,797
Y-yeah, it's finished.
It's right in front of you.

613
00:36:53,654 --> 00:36:57,159
- What was it doing behind the couch?
- It's a long story.

614
00:36:57,259 --> 00:36:59,878
- <i>Bye Bye, Grandma?</i>
- It's a working title.

615
00:36:59,978 --> 00:37:02,478
I'm also thinking of
<i>What Happened to Grandma?</i>

616
00:37:03,149 --> 00:37:07,336
<i>Bye Bye, Grandma.</i>
It's cute, I like it.

617
00:37:07,436 --> 00:37:09,672
The great thing is,
it's a pop-up book.

618
00:37:09,772 --> 00:37:11,283
We don't do pop-ups.

619
00:37:12,588 --> 00:37:14,061
It's something new.

620
00:37:16,144 --> 00:37:19,765
Yes... A pop-up.

621
00:37:23,483 --> 00:37:24,674
Oh!

622
00:37:25,192 --> 00:37:26,560
What is this?

623
00:37:26,660 --> 00:37:28,676
This is sick!
We can't sell that!

624
00:37:28,776 --> 00:37:31,034
- Why not?
- Because it's not nice!

625
00:37:31,460 --> 00:37:34,331
Of course it's not nice!
Death rarely is.

626
00:37:34,431 --> 00:37:35,356
Death?

627
00:37:35,456 --> 00:37:38,704
What are you writing about death for?
These are children's books!

628
00:37:38,804 --> 00:37:40,924
Death is the last thing
on their minds!

629
00:37:41,024 --> 00:37:42,824
Why can't you write about
bunnies or something?

630
00:37:42,924 --> 00:37:44,750
I don't wanna
write about bunnies!

631
00:37:44,850 --> 00:37:48,188
- Look at Murray Craig.
- Please, don't bring up Murray Craig.

632
00:37:48,288 --> 00:37:51,678
- Murray Craig is our top writer.
- I know Murray Craig is the top writer!

633
00:37:51,778 --> 00:37:53,818
I know Murray Craig
makes a lot of money!

634
00:37:53,918 --> 00:37:56,463
But Murray Craig has
the mind of an ostrich!

635
00:37:56,563 --> 00:37:58,574
- His books sell!
- He's uncreative!

636
00:37:58,674 --> 00:38:02,469
He is not uncreative.
He is the creator of Happy the Clam.

637
00:38:02,569 --> 00:38:04,922
P-please, please, don't bring up
Happy the Clam.

638
00:38:05,022 --> 00:38:08,263
Happy the Clam is,
and has been for the past 10 years,

639
00:38:08,363 --> 00:38:11,304
our number one marketable figure.
Everyone loves Happy the Clam.

640
00:38:11,404 --> 00:38:13,597
Children love Happy the Clam.
Parents love Happy the Clam.

641
00:38:13,697 --> 00:38:15,948
My husband and I
both love Happy the Clam.

642
00:38:16,048 --> 00:38:18,795
- It's a stupid concept!
- It is not a stupid concept!

643
00:38:18,895 --> 00:38:22,190
It's a clam!
A clam!

644
00:38:22,290 --> 00:38:26,591
Could you possibly pick
a more distant, non-feeling,

645
00:38:26,691 --> 00:38:29,181
totally unemotional...
thing!

646
00:38:29,281 --> 00:38:31,426
I mean, they have
no distinguishable features,

647
00:38:31,526 --> 00:38:33,592
absolutely no
measureable intelligence,

648
00:38:33,692 --> 00:38:36,175
they're disgusting,
squishy...!

649
00:38:40,406 --> 00:38:42,234
I mean, look at this.
Look at it!

650
00:38:42,334 --> 00:38:47,292
There's legs sticking out of its shell,
it's sideways, and of course, a hat!

651
00:38:47,392 --> 00:38:49,175
A clam with a hat!

652
00:38:49,275 --> 00:38:51,602
"Oh look, honey, the Clams
have come over for dinner!"

653
00:38:51,702 --> 00:38:55,048
"Hello, Mr. Clam. Would you
like me to take your... hat?!"

654
00:38:55,148 --> 00:38:57,644
Happy the Clam
is a mindless creation!

655
00:38:57,744 --> 00:39:01,002
There is nothing appealing about him!
There is nothing redeeming about him!

656
00:39:01,102 --> 00:39:05,196
He represents everything
I hate in life!

657
00:39:05,296 --> 00:39:07,229
I hate him!
I always have hated him!

658
00:39:07,329 --> 00:39:12,477
I always will hate him!
I hate Happy the Clam!

659
00:39:12,577 --> 00:39:17,516
I will not sit here and listen to you
badmouth Happy the Clam!

660
00:39:17,616 --> 00:39:22,186
If you are looking to lose your job,
mister, you are on the right track!

661
00:39:22,286 --> 00:39:24,483
This company
was founded 12 years ago,

662
00:39:24,583 --> 00:39:27,684
and thanks to Murray's creation
of Happy the Clam,

663
00:39:27,784 --> 00:39:31,651
for the past 10 years,
has been showing a sizable profit!

664
00:39:31,751 --> 00:39:33,698
So you may not like
Happy the Clam,

665
00:39:33,798 --> 00:39:35,877
but Happy the Clam
pays the bills!

666
00:39:35,977 --> 00:39:39,372
And whether you like it or not,
if it weren't for Happy the Clam,

667
00:39:39,472 --> 00:39:43,441
you wouldn't have a job!

668
00:39:47,657 --> 00:39:49,530
Maybe I--maybe I was
a little rash.

669
00:39:50,933 --> 00:39:53,146
I have to...
I have to apologize.

670
00:39:54,015 --> 00:39:58,779
I did forget one key use
for Happy the Clam.

671
00:39:58,879 --> 00:40:03,970
I forgot that Happy the Clam
could be rolled up into a little ball,

672
00:40:04,070 --> 00:40:06,377
and shoved up your butt!

673
00:40:06,477 --> 00:40:08,979
That's what I forgot!
Silly me!

674
00:40:09,079 --> 00:40:12,513
And as far as the company
being here for 12 years,

675
00:40:12,613 --> 00:40:14,132
how would you know?

676
00:40:14,232 --> 00:40:17,399
You've only been
screwing up things for 2!

677
00:40:17,499 --> 00:40:20,497
And now, let's analyze
how she got the job.

678
00:40:20,597 --> 00:40:22,993
Did she graduate
from college? Ehh!

679
00:40:23,093 --> 00:40:26,380
Did she study her craft
for long hours? Ehh!

680
00:40:26,480 --> 00:40:29,877
Well, then surely she inherited
the business from her father? Ehh!

681
00:40:29,977 --> 00:40:34,624
You know how she got the job?
She slept with the boss!

682
00:40:34,724 --> 00:40:36,946
That's how she got the job!

683
00:40:39,480 --> 00:40:42,781
Oh, no!
So soon?

684
00:40:43,007 --> 00:40:46,777
Please come back!
I love these little chats we have!

685
00:40:46,877 --> 00:40:49,681
Surely, you can stay
a little longer?

686
00:40:54,994 --> 00:40:56,515
What have I done?

687
00:40:56,615 --> 00:41:00,826
My job! Ugh!
How am I gonna eat?

688
00:41:10,289 --> 00:41:13,272
I... I was...

689
00:41:13,372 --> 00:41:15,948
I was never crazy
about that job, anyway.

690
00:41:24,054 --> 00:41:25,295
Smokers.

691
00:41:26,797 --> 00:41:29,415
There's no excuse
for smoking.

692
00:41:30,444 --> 00:41:32,700
I can't stand smoke.

693
00:41:33,476 --> 00:41:37,575
A hobby that makes you die.

694
00:41:38,884 --> 00:41:42,566
I mean, that's the equivalent
of always carrying around a salt lick

695
00:41:42,666 --> 00:41:45,024
laced with a tiny bit
of cyanide.

696
00:41:45,124 --> 00:41:48,479
"Hey, what are you doing?"
"Oh, nothing, just a hobby."

697
00:41:50,307 --> 00:41:53,573
"Whoa...
I'm getting kinda dizzy."

698
00:41:55,476 --> 00:41:57,461
What about people
who say they're gonna quit,

699
00:41:57,561 --> 00:41:59,207
and you see them,
like an hour later,

700
00:41:59,307 --> 00:42:01,072
with a butt hanging
out of their mouth?

